name: Beacon Hill Cottage in the City
summary: A small cottage for a single traveler or a cozy couple.  You'll be nestled into a little spot of greenery amidst an urban backdrop.  Beacon Hill gives you easy access to the city by bus and a light rail station within walking distance.  You'll be immersed in one of the most diverse neighborhoods offering a wide variety of restaurants and cafes.  Feel free to ask me questions! I can help you decide how to enjoy our area by foot, bus, train or car.
space: Ideal for a single visitor or cozy couple.  Often described as feeling 'European'. The Cottage is a bedroom with your own bathroom and shower. A deck overlooking a peaceful garden. Private off-street parking (our driveway) is available. A gravel driveway leads you to a hidden urban oasis in the middle of a pleasant city block set back from the street. The garden separates you from our home, giving you a view of greenery to enjoy from the deck. We do not offer a kitchen as the Cottage is intended for short visits. We do offer a hot water kettle, a small refrigerator (loaded with complimentary beverages) and Via instant coffee. Wi-Fi and Netflix No smoking No pets or children. The #36 bus is across the street and will take you downtown in 20 minutes.   We are gay, race and age friendly and expect that you are too!

notes: Tall visitors, if you're over 6 feet, the shower may be a little short for you, my apologies. (a dear friend of 6'5‰Û during his visit chuckled at this and still loves me despite)! Transportation: On foot and coming from the SeaTac Airport; take the Light Rail and get off at the Beacon Hill stop.  From there, the Cottage is a short bus ride heading South on the #36.  Renting a car; 20-minute drive from SeaTac Airport. Arriving on Amtrak; walk up to Jackson Street and take the #36 going South. It will drop you off within steps of the Cottage.
transit: The Light Rail station is 2 miles away with easy access to the International District, Capitol Hill, Downtown, University District, Husky Stadium, CenturyLink Stadium, Safeco Field, Seattle Art Museum, and Westlake Center. Pike Place Market is a 20-minute bus ride.
access: The cottage is separate from our house so you'll have access to the cottage once you enter our property.
interaction: You'll get a personal greeting as I live here.  I believe that is why most people take this route so they can have a human experience.   A bit of communication and warm hospitality goes a long way. It's easy to draw from my own travels so I try to show the same warmth I've experienced and apply it as a host.  The Cottage has a steady rotation of guests coming for business, visiting family, special occasions or simply getting away for some rest and relaxation.  Each traveling situation has a set of its own circumstances and you'll be able to simply fall into your groove and unfold your story.
house_rules: I believe there is an unspoken language among respectful travelers, that you treat someone's home as if it were your own. We are gay, race and age friendly and expect that you are too! No smoking. No pets or children. Seasoned travelers will intuitively know what is expected of them so I don't feel the need to enforce common courtesy. I trust my guests will come here with all those bases covered.
host_about: I love gardening and the cottage is surrounded by my efforts of creating a nest of greenery amidst the hustle and bustle of the city, giving you a place to nestle in for a pleasant urban experience.

name: Modern, Light-Filled Fremont Flat
summary: Artful. Bright. Clean. Comfortable. Peaceful.
space: Southwest-facing sunny deck, big windows on 3 sides, beautiful sunsets and views of the surrounding neighborhoods and the Olympic mountains, steps away from all the action: this top-floor, 1-bedroom apartment is a great place to stay during your Seattle visit.   The apartment has a queen-sized bed with a comfortable luxury mattress and it is perfect for 1 or 2 people. Other features include hardwood floors, washer and dryer, dishwasher, WiFi, bathroom with a skylight, deck with sitting bench, original artwork, and a rooftop deck. The nice fully-equipped kitchen is stocked with some essentials for your convenience.
description: Artful. Bright. Clean. Comfortable. Peaceful. Southwest-facing sunny deck, big windows on 3 sides, beautiful sunsets and views of the surrounding neighborhoods and the Olympic mountains, steps away from all the action: this top-floor, 1-bedroom apartment is a great place to stay during your Seattle visit.   The apartment has a queen-sized bed with a comfortable luxury mattress and it is perfect for 1 or 2 people. Other features include hardwood floors, washer and dryer, dishwasher, WiFi, bathroom with a skylight, deck with sitting bench, original artwork, and a rooftop deck. The nice fully-equipped kitchen is stocked with some essentials for your convenience. Guests can enjoy access to the rooftop deck. Parking is on the street and it is not difficult to find a spot within 1-2 blocks. Free reserved garage parking spot may be available for month-long or longer stays. I will welcome you, show you around the apartment, and gladly give you suggestions and ideas for things to do in the area
neighborhood_overview: The apartment is conveniently located in the heart of Fremont, one of the best neighborhoods for experiencing true Seattle urban lifestyle: walk to coffee shops, a local natural grocery store (PCC), many restaurants, pubs, boutiques, live music, a theater, the open-air Sunday market, a real chocolate factory, and the Fremont library. The ship canal with park benches and a 40-mile biking/walking path (Burke-Gilman) is only minutes away on foot. Fremont buzzes with activity daily, and especially on Friday and Saturday evenings.
notes: This is a "no outside shoes" home and smoking is not allowed in the building. WiFi is available; there are speakers with a music player hook-up, but no television set. I kindly ask guests to coordinate check-in and check-out times a few days in advance. In general, most times should work as long as I have some notice; we can figure out the exact times via e-mail. Please note that an additional cleaning fee of $120-160 (exact amount depending on the condition you leave the apartment in) applies for stays longer than 2 weeks and this amount will be requested for deduction from the deposit after checkout.
transit: The apartment is a 10 to 15-minute bus ride to downtown (bus lines 5, 26/28, and 40) and 10 minutes to the University district (bus lines 31, 32).
access: Guests can enjoy access to the rooftop deck. Parking is on the street and it is not difficult to find a spot within 1-2 blocks. Free reserved garage parking spot may be available for month-long or longer stays.
interaction: I will welcome you, show you around the apartment, and gladly give you suggestions and ideas for things to do in the area, or answer any questions you might have. I let you decide on the amount of interaction with me.
house_rules: Please note that this is not a hotel. Please leave the space as you found it and live in it with care. Smoking is not allowed anywhere in the building.  Pets are not allowed in the apartment. I ask that no outside shoes are worn inside the apartment.  Please remove your trash, recyclables, and food waste before check-out. Other information to ensure a comfortable stay for you will be provided upon your arrival. I am always glad to answer questions about the neighborhood, Seattle or the area so don't hesitate to ask! I look forward to meeting you and sharing my home with you. I hope you have a fabulous visit. Longer-term guests: please only use the natural cleaning supplies provided in the apartment. If you need any other cleaning supplies, PCC Natural Markets down the street carries non-toxic cleaning products. Thank you for keeping my home as chemical-free as possible for the sake of everyone's health. Thank you!
host_about: Hi! I am Danni. I love to travel, to meet other travelers and to share my Seattle apartment. I take pride in keeping it clean and comfortable.I grew up in Sofia, Bulgaria and have lived more than half of my life in the US, of which 12 years in Seattle. I have also lived in Minneapolis, MN; Ft. Worth, TX; Maastricht, the Netherlands; Brussels, Belgium; and Barcelona, Spain. I am an adventure seeker, a bike commuter, a hiker/backpacker/climber, an avid traveler, a nutrition professor, a vegetarian, and most recently, a mother of a beautiful little girl. Life is better with my daughter, mountains, good food, poetry, a bicycle, and engaging conversations. I live for human connections, new experiences and ideas. When I travel, I love connecting with locals, going off the beaten path (and learning some of the local language) because these all give me a much richer experience. When I host, I care about my guests' comfort and try to help them experience the unique beauty of Seattle and the Pacific Northwest.

house_rules: Please contact me before you make a reservation. The main house rule is the Golden Rule.  I'm still practicing but am pretty good at it and hope you are too.   Here's an example:  If you are having overnight guests yourself/ves, I would like to know that.   Another example:  There's room in the driveway for three cars.  If you're having guests, let me know and I'll show you where I park when I have guests!
host_about: Airbnb is a way to have a houseful, which is what I like.  Ever since I was a kid doing sleepovers to my first job out of college as a Peace Corps Volunteer in Turkey all through my long and longer life, I've loved every place I've ever visited.  So maybe that's why I want to return all the great hospitality I've received.These days I'm a realtime captioner for hard of hearing.  Which means I go to classes, meetings, conferences with students (or staff or faculty) primarily at the University of Washington and write live everything being said so the student can read it on my computer screen as it's happening.  You've seen closed captioning on TV?  It's like that, only I'm there live on site.  Love my job.  It's challenging (that is to say, hard) and can be stressful, but I am glad to be a vehicle for access to education and the workplace that people wouldn't have without that service.  The service is provided under auspices of the Americans with Disabilities Act.There are so many things to do in Seattle, and I am happy to give you information and ideas for your stay -- or just get out of your way and let you have at it!

name: Teeny Tiny Guestyhouse!
summary: It's a Teeny Tiny Guesthouse!  Enter the words "tiny guesthouse tour" in your search engine or follow the instructions in the 2nd photo to see the video.  Trust me, it's totally worth it!  Also, click on the photo for more photos.  :) The price is the price.  No hidden extra "cleaning" charges!  Those are for the hosts who want to scam you.  But that's not really my thing.  Trust me, have I ever lied to you?
space: Don't worry, the Tiny Guesthouse has heat.  Very cozy this time of year. I built a teeny tiny guesthouse in my backyard, between the Garage Majal and the old millworkers house in the middle of Seattle's exciting Fremont neighborhood!  It's 68 sq' and can sleep 3 (if two of the three are a couple) using the sleeping loft that lets out onto the rooftop view lawn or, my not yet patented, "Garage Door Murphy Bed".  There's a teeny tiny full bath (toilet, sink, shower) and a secret bathtub beneath the floor.  It is private from the other living areas on the property although, being right in town, stepping outside may put you in contact with (gasp!) actual other people.  There are times when people hang out to chat, BBQ, sing and laugh downstairs, as it should be.  Remeber, this is in the city.  It's not a quiet retreat for the noise sensitive.  That said, I've gotten very few complaints about noise.  There is no TV but good fast wifi for your laptop and a cool old radio with iPod plug in!

neighborhood_overview: Fremont is about a 10 minute bus ride from downtown.  Seattle lives in its neighborhoods and this is one of it's best ones.  From my place you can walk 2 blocks into the center of things where you can find enough to entertain you for days on end.  Want to go up to Ballard, over to Gasworks Park, or downtown?  Grab a bike and be anywhere in 10-15 minutes!
notes: I have several loaner bikes that your're welcome to use.  In Seattle you're "supposed" to wear a helmet so bring one if you like to follow the rules...
transit: There are tons of bus lines all within a few blocks that will take you most anywhere.  I'm also close to the Burke Gilman bicycle trail as well as several bike trails to downtown.
access: There's a small "grotto lawn" outside the guesthouse that's nice to hang out on in good weather.  Below that is a private residence and I usually ask folks not to go down there unless invited by the tenants.
interaction: As much or as little as you like.  It's a private space.  Some folks and I hit it off and visit a lot.  Others I never see.  All depends on the circumstance.
house_rules: If you break anything, please tell me so I can fix it.  Input on improvements in liveablility and reliablility is very much appreciated as this is really a laboratory for small living.  I think I got a lot of stuff right but only actual experience will tell.   Please, please, please, don't park in my neighbors driveway (yellow garage) even "just for a minute".  It a fragile relationship that is currently under repair and, while they'd never say anything, I can feel their looks when someone has... I provide lots of sheets and pillowcases.  Please use them.  I know it's nice to wrap yourself in a fluffy comforter but then I have to wash a fluffy comforter which is an entire load all on it's own.  Sheets, on the other hand, can share a load with towels and let me do it all in one load.  Also, while I'm on the subject and being a big crybaby, please leave your sleeping bags and such in your car.  I don't want to find out one day that critters have arrived on someones camping gear and have
host_about: If I had to find one word to describe myself I wouldn't...

name: Mother-in-Law Apartment in Seattle
summary: Perfect for visiting family in Seattle.  Our mother-in-law apartment is located in the Green Lake/Wallingford area with great parks and restaurants just around the corner.  We have a small market (56th Street market) and micro-brewery in the neighborhood (Tangletown Pub).  We even have an organic, vegan donut shop around the corner call Mighty O Donuts.  And you can get one of the best cups of coffee in Seattle at Zoka's. There's a bus stop that will get connect you to the rest of Seattle.

neighborhood_overview: In the early 1900's Seattle had a thriving streetcar system that serviced the entire city.  Tangletown was the major transfer point for the streetcar system with all roads leading to the area.  Today those disjointed roads meet in a vibrant community that has a lake, great parks, excellent food, locally brewed beer, fantastic coffee, organic donuts and much more.
notes: If you drive to Seattle there is plenty of unrestricted parking on the street.  We'll help you navigate the city if you have any questions.
transit: Just around the corner from our house is the #62 bus stop.  From there you can go directly to downtown Seattle, Seattle Center or .  You don't need a car to get anywhere in the city if you are willing to take the bus.  however, you may have to make a transfer to get to your final destination.
access: The apartment has a separate entrance that give our guest lots of privacy.  The entrance opens to our backyard garden.
interaction: Ralph will welcome you and get you settled into the apartment.  Once you have the key you are free to come and go as you please.  If you have any questions or needs just let us know.
house_rules: House Rules ‰Û¢	No Smoking ‰Û¢	Ask If You Need Anything ‰Û¢	Treat Our Apartment Like Your Own ‰Û¢	Say ‰ÛÏHello‰Û When You Have The Chance
host_about: Hello my name is Ralph.  I'm a full-time photographer/graphic design with a life long fascination with Seattle.  You can see my (Email hidden by Airbnb)  You will also see some of my Seattle work on the walls of the apartment.  If you are interested in turning a portion of your visit into a photography workshop that results in artwork you create please let me know.  I can definitely help you if you are interested in the Seattle Art scene.For 30 years Ralph specialized in community-based tropical agriculture. His job took him all over the world. One of the benefits was that he got to meet all kinds of interesting people, something he enjoys. So he can help you find the best, reasonably price ethnic food in Seattle.  I hope we get to meet during one of your stays.

summary: Green Lake Guest Suite is a two-bedroom 900 sf apartment in a daylight basement with two queen beds, futon, private bath with shower, private entry, kitchen, shared patio and shared laundry. Owners live on-site.
space: The apartment is perfect for up to 6 people that want a residential retreat in a vital Seattle neighborhood with the option to prepare all your meals in house. Amenities include Wifi internet, TV, Netflix streaming, heating, air conditioning, hair dryer, linens, coffee and tea. It is the lower level of a house with owners living in the separate main floor unit.
description: Green Lake Guest Suite is a two-bedroom 900 sf apartment in a daylight basement with two queen beds, futon, private bath with shower, private entry, kitchen, shared patio and shared laundry. Owners live on-site. The apartment is perfect for up to 6 people that want a residential retreat in a vital Seattle neighborhood with the option to prepare all your meals in house. Amenities include Wifi internet, TV, Netflix streaming, heating, air conditioning, hair dryer, linens, coffee and tea. Laundry, BBQ and patio are shared space with the owners. Our apartment is half of our duplex house, so we are close by. We like to give guests their privacy, but we are available any time for questions or needs. Seattle is among the most active cities in the U.S. and Green Lake is Seattle‰Ûªs hub for recreation. Circling the lake is a walk
neighborhood_overview: Seattle is among the most active cities in the U.S. and Green Lake is Seattle‰Ûªs hub for recreation. Circling the lake is a walking/running/wheels trail 2.8 miles round trip. The park offers tennis and basketball courts, baseball and soccer fields, golf course, public swimming beaches, boat/kayak/paddle board rentals, and a theatre. The trail is also a great place for people watching and the best way to access many restaurants and shops lining the lake.
notes: Kids: We don't have kids, and our apartment is not very kid-friendly, especially for children under 8. We find that small children often run wherever they go, and heavy footsteps carry upstairs to our space, as well as other loud noises. Kids also typically bring a measure of extra cleaning. That being said, we have been pleasantly surprised by several guests with small children who were quiet and clean! So we do welcome children and infants, and they are counted as additional guests in our rate calculations. No Cleaning Fee: We previously charged a cleaning fee for each stay. However, we found that 90% of guests automatically cleaned up before checking out. So instead, we have a simple Cleaning Checklist that guests are asked to complete before checking out. It allows us to quickly get the apartment ready for the next guests. For guests that choose not to follow the cleaning list, we charge a cleaning fee of up to $50 from the security deposit. Supplies: We provide you with enough toi
transit: Just around the corner from beautiful Green Lake Park, 10-minute drive to Downtown and University of Washington, and a short 2-block walk to city bus stops. One block to restaurants along the lake, and two blocks from a natural organic foods market.
access: The apartment is accessed by a keyless lock. You will be assigned a four-digit code. Laundry, BBQ and patio are shared space with the owners.
interaction: Our apartment is half of our duplex house, so we are close by. We like to give guests their privacy, but we are available any time for questions or needs.
house_rules: - Additional guests = $20/day/person (6 guests maximum; children and infants included). - Remove shoes inside the house. - Quiet hours from 10:00pm to 7:00am.  - Recycling and composting is required. - Futon as a bed only for 5-6 guest reservations. - $400 security/damage deposit (credit card hold). - Cleaning List is required at check-out or a cleaning fee of up to $50 may be charged.
host_about: I'm a school psychologist serving public elementary schools. Along with my husband's support, I have rented our home on Airbnb since 2011. We have had such a wonderful experience with Airbnb guests from around the world and have made many new friendships. We love our house and our "Utopian" neighborhood of Green Lake, and we're excited to share them with you. The house is comprised of upper and lower 2-bedroom complete units, and we live in the main unit, so we are often on hand to help with anything you may need. The "other pets" we own are adorable house rabbits that provide nonstop entertainment (let us know if you would like to meet the bunnies).

notes: Bedrooms are close together in one hallway. Checkin: Arrange during booking process so we can be here to let you in. Generally between 4PM and 10PM. Checkout: 11 AM Free street parking. Well lit.
transit: It's somewhat convenient to get around without a car. The lite rail train takes you downtown or to the airport and we're a mile from the station. With out a car you can use Uber or Lyft or walk two blocks to a bus which will take you to the train.

house_rules: No Smoking anywhere on property. Shoes off in main part of house. Quiet after 11 pm. No extra people.
host_about: My Husband and I have lived in Seattle since 1989. He's a computer network architect/engineer and I'm a teaching artist. We're active middle-agers and enjoy biking, hiking, skiing and walking. We're exuberant and outgoing. Love exploring new places and getting to know new people. We can also be happy cozied up with a good book.

name: Main floor of comfy craftsman home
summary: Centrally located, quiet and cozy home away from home invites you to relax and get comfortable as soon as you enter. This solar powered home is close to bus lines, parks, shops, downtown Seattle and the Eastside.
space: Charming 100 year old craftsman home offers hospitality and comfort for your visit to Seattle. Nestled in a quiet neighborhood close to Lake Washington and only a 15 minute bus ride into downtown, it is very convenient to much of what the Seattle area has to offer. Artistic and inviting, the main floor of the house has a large open plan living/dining room area, well equipped kitchen, full bath, and two comfy bedrooms. On street parking is free and readily available.

neighborhood_overview: The Leschi neighborhood is quiet, diverse and thriving. There are lovely walks down to the lake and nearby parks, and we are within walking distance of some great restaurants and coffee shops. You'll be provided with a walking map to acquaint you with the area. Plenty of suggestions for Seattle activities, in particular the Pike Place Market where Sara operates her crafts business.
notes: There is a garden and back deck you are welcome to enjoy. I have a friendly young dog you may encounter in the back yard which is shared.
transit: Close to bus lines, you can get downtown Seattle in less than 20 minutes. Near light rail Mount Baker stop so easy access to and from the airport. Parking is free, on the street, and readily available.
access: The main floor is all yours with your host, Sara, living downstairs in a separate apartment. The home is solar powered, Netflix and WiFi, full bath, kitchen and two bedrooms. Both bedrooms have comfortable beds, one full, one queen, plus each has a reading chair, desk and closet space. The well equipped kitchen is stocked with breakfast fixings (organic when possible), plus you can make use of cooking basics such as olive oil, herbs and spices, sugar and flour, etc. The stove is gas, there is a microwave and dishwasher plus other handy kitchen gadgets if you're planning to cook (juicer, blender).
interaction: While I enjoy getting to know travelers and sharing any insights I might have on the area, I respect guests privacy and am careful not to interfere. I live in a separate unit downstairs.
house_rules: No smoking in the house Shoes off at the door if wet or muddy Dispose of all trash, recycling and food waste correctly No check in after midnight or before 8 am. Prearrange  check in Keep house secure by locking windows and doors whenever you leave
host_about: Greetings traveller! I am an artist and have been a crafts vendor at the colorful Pike Place Market for more than three decades. I love traveling and have family as far flung as the Norwegian arctic circle and West Africa. My travel experiences have been so enriching and everywhere I go I'm grateful for the kindness and generosity of hosts. I strive to offer the same quality of experience with people who come to share in the beauty of the Northwest or explore the Seattle area. You will be welcome to make yourselves at home here and use the outdoor spaces.  I love to garden so there are yummy morsels to nibble on occasion and I invite birds and squirrels to share the yard so please be kind. While I enjoy getting to know guests I also respect people's space and privacy and strive to be sensitive to your needs. I try to practice: live simply so that others can simply live.

name: Metrobilly Retreat
summary: Your hideout in Seattle! Surround yourself with trees, birds and calm while you visit the Pacific Northwest. Our little bit of country in the city to share. We can't wait to meet you!
space: Hello and Thanks for stopping by! We welcome everyone from all imaginable walks of life! Private basement bedroom for one or two guests with a cozy queen size bed and full, attached and private bathroom in 100+ year old Seattle craftsman home. The room contains most of our library, so you will be able to dive into a new read or revisit an old favorite! Electric kettle for coffee and tea, included for you. Store a few yummy treats in the mini fridge, make a quick meal in the microwave, or come upstairs and share our fully equipped kitchen for a more elaborate feast!  Kids are welcome!  Pets are negotiable, please ask Cosmo, our nine year old pooch, looks forward to meeting you too! Parking is free and available on the street. Separate keypad lock entrance through the bicycle/mud room allows you to come and go as you please. neighborhood_overview: Madison Valley is in between Capitol Hill to the west and Madison Park and Lake Washington to the east. Just north is the extensive grounds of the University of Washington's Arboretum and the Japanese Garden. To the south is the Madrona neighborhood and the Central District...think Ethiopian restaurants...yum! We are within walking distance to some excellent restaurants, a small grocery for that essential pint of ice cream and some neat retail spots. The forest like atmosphere is very cozy and relaxing. Walking in the neighborhood is beautiful...and invigorating as we boast some very steep hills. The views once you climb are amazing! There are also two miniature horses a few blocks away that you can visit and may get to pet!
transit: Transit: Our closest Seattle Metro bus lines are #8 and #11. The #8 takes you to the Seattle Center and Queen Anne neighborhood via Capitol Hill or to Beacon Hill if you go south. The #11 runs up to Capitol Hill and to Downtown. Each run about every 15 minutes during the day and about every 30 minutes at night. The bus stops are about a ten minute walk. King County has a trip planning website that will help: type in King Country metro trip planner to find the site. Parking is free and available on the street. To get to us from the SeaTac airport, you can: (1) take the Central Link Light Rail for about $5.00 for a 40 minute ride to downtown Seattle or Capitol Hill Station, then walk to the bus #8 or #11. This is operated by Sound Transit and you can find the trip planner on their site. They suggest taking the bus #8 from the Beacon Hill or Mount Baker station, and that works too.   (2) Schedule via online reservation to take the Airporter Shuttle. They will drop you at our driveway. It
access: Shared laundry, shared kitchen and yard/fire pit (weather permitting). Separate entry gives you plenty of freedom. Guests are welcome to cook and eat in the kitchen or back yard. If you need kitchen shelf space, especially for a longer stay, please ask!
interaction: We live in the same house! Sometimes I don't get a chance to meet you, and other times we collide and have long conversations! Because you have your own entrance, you are free to come and go. I am happy to help with questions or Seattle-seeing-strategies, or to leave you to your own devices (which usually means great friends in the area!) Either way depends on personalities, agendas and timing.
house_rules: --Please let us know your arrival and departure plans, once you know them! --Smoking allowed outside. Recreational marijuana is legal in Washington. Please smoke outside. If it's pouring rain, please smoke on the porch outside! Thank you! --Please lock the door if you are leaving the house. --Please turn off the porch light and mud room light once you are in for the night. I will do my best to turn them on in the evening, if you are out. --Seattle is working hard to reduce our land fills! -Please recycle clean paper, glass and plastics in the labeled container in the closet.  -Organic waste: food scraps, bio-stuff, tissues or food-soiled paper (pizza and take-out boxes) can all go in the green container in the bathroom. More bio bags are under the sink. --Pets! We've hosted a great many dogs, cats and one bunny at the Metrobilly! Our dog gets really excited about any pet visitors, so we ask common sense and to make arrangements for the dogs to meet if you want them to! Cosmo gets along
host_about: Hi There! My husband and I welcome you to our Metrobilly Retreat! It's slowly getting less rough around the edges, as we each find time to work on projects. We are both artists and create chiefly with metals; my work is generally small and often wearable, whereas my husband makes bicycles and pieces on a larger scale.We practice yoga and keep fit with cycling and exercising our dogs, and attempt to keep our brains working.We are teaching ourselves to make wine and cider, and transforming our patch of land into a garden with edible and colorful characters.We both spent our growing years traveling/moving, and currently travel every chance we can get. This means, we know how important it is to be comfortable, cozy and worry free. We are delighted to help you feel at home as you adventure out into Seattle!

name: N. Beacon Hill- Super Private Room
summary: Welcome! We love to host Airbnb guests but we give you lots and lots of privacy. You will be our only guest and you likely won‰Ûªt see us unless you seek us out. Ask us anything but we won‰Ûªt bother you if you prefer to stay on your own. We want you to enjoy your stay, no matter what that means to you. Beacon hill is a fantastic neighborhood ‰ÛÒ great for walking around and grabbing a bite to eat. The light rail is a 10 minute walk and that gets you to downtown or the airport in no time.
space: Hi! We are Jana and Nick and we'd love to have you stay in our guest room. It has it's own en suite bath and is far away from the rest of the house, so you can have complete privacy.  The room has a queen size bed (with an awesome mattress), small TV with cable and a big closet. Our house is only a few years old, so everything is clean and fresh.  We provide shampoo, conditioner, shower gel, and hair dryer, so you may be able to get away with packing a little lighter.  We live in a townhouse and the bedroom is on the bottom floor. It can get a little cool down there (great in the summer!) but if you ever get chilly, you have your own thermostat, so you can adjust it to your liking.  The room has a huge window so you get tons of natural light. The great part is the house is insulated wonderfully so you will never hear us and we will never hear you! No Smoking in the room.  No Pets No cooking in the room Feel free to use the entry hallway to store your luggage if you arrive early or after the check out time.  Please refrain from going upstairs from the entryway. That is the private area of our home.
host_about: I'm Jana and my husband is Nick. We live in Seattle and are Airbnb hosts ourselves! Nick is a tech guy and I'm working on my MBA. We love to explore new places and soak in a new city.

name: Private 1BR, Parking, Eco-Cleaned, 5% to Charity
summary: This artistic 1-bedroom apartment on the ground floor of a classic 1931 home is designed for travelers who appreciate a quiet oasis in Seattle‰Ûªs urban Central District neighborhood. Private entrance with key code entry. Kitchenette. Full bath. WiFi. Laundry. Magical garden! Walk to cafes, p-patch garden, restaurants. Steps to buses (#2, 3, 8, 48) to downtown, Pike Place market, Space Needle. Free street parking, 100% natural green clean, fragrance-free home. 5% donated to local charities!
space: My guest space is a fully furnished one-bedroom basement apt with a full bath, living room and small kitchenette with your own private entrance and access to a tiny magical garden. Quiet urban retreat with music, books and maps on Seattle parks and neighborhood local hot spots (Cortona Cafe, Katy's, St. Clouds, Hi-Spot), wifi, popcorn, chocolate, coffee, tea and snacks provided.  Walk 1-3 blocks to 4 buses. On street parking is free. Sales tax included. A cable TV with a DVD player is provided for watching movies.  5% of all proceeds are split between two community agencies:  - The Urban Rest Stop for the homeless in Seattle and  - Coyote Central, an innovative Central District Youth Arts organization Fragrance Free We are a fragrance-free airbnb to accommodate guests with asthma, and chemical sensitivities and to improve awareness for all people regarding fragrance chemicals. Thank you for not wearing  perfume, cologne, and for not using other scented products.

neighborhood_overview: Foot friendly with lots of community gardens, called p-patches! I am in a neighborhood called the Central District (locals call it 'The CD') between the fantastic local eateries and shops in nearby Capitol Hill and Madrona 'hoods.' Like many US cities, the CD neighborhood has both has million dollar homes as well as a homeless population.
notes: This is rarely an issue for guests. I do provide a white noise sound blocker and earplugs for the few light sleepers who have been disturbed by noise when there is construction or when the furnace starts. You can always ask me to turn off the furnace (assuming you are warm enough).
transit: Centrally located. High walkability score! Steps to cafes, restaurants. Four buses in a 3 block radius to downtown, Pike Place Market, Pioneer Square, Convention Center, Lake Washington, Capitol Hill and the University district.
access: Enjoy a fully furnished art-filled 1 bedroom home-away-from-home with a separate living area with a 'fireplace,' fantastic cork floors, hand-plastered ochre bathroom (cozy soft towels, organic locally-made bed and cotton sheets) and a small kitchenette (refrigerator, toaster-oven, 1 burner hotplate, microwave, dishes, pots, pans). There is a double bed and one twin sofa bed as well as a double air mattress. A washer/dryer is available for one load at no charge and $5 fee for each additional load. The apartment has a private entrance with key-code entry that is changed between guests. No need to deal with the hassle of getting or returning keys!
interaction: Guests have total privacy. I send a text message to check-in once or twice. If guests have questions, I am available by text or phone. If you enjoy nature, I offer an Airbnb experience as well. Check it out, it's a tranquil meditative walk in the old growth forest in Seattle: https://www.airbnb.com/experiences/62024?location=Seattle%2C%20WA%2098122%2C%20United%20States&source=p2å_tTab=experience_tab&searchId=c0457467-3cdf-4f5b-ad2e-d78c4605c049&recommended_instance_id=333317
house_rules: I appreciate when guests respect my home and garden. Please be considerate when interacting with my friendly neighbors. Please recycle and be mindful of water and electricity consumption. I am trying to keep a small environmental footprint. I welcome questions about living with a 'light' footprint and living mindfully.  If something is damaged, be sure to let me know prior to leaving so I can fix it in time for the next guests. No shoes please. No pets please.  No smoking. No fragrance (no colognes or perfumes or dryer sheets). Please provide ID for verification.
host_about: I enjoy traveling and hosting guests in a modern, sustainable, eco-designed, private, 1 bedroom garden apartment. I am a quiet Ph.D. researcher and documentary film enthusiast. I enjoy sharing my favorite Seattle coffee shops, parks, cinemas, and book stores. Many of my guests are researchers, filmmakers, designers, writers, academics, artists, musicians, and families visiting relatives. I like meeting fellow independent travelers who enjoy meandering through urban neighborhoods. If you enjoy nature, I offer an Airbnb experience as well. Check it out, it's a tranquil meditative walk in the old growth forest in Seattle: https://www.airbnb.com/experiences/62024?location=Seattle%2C%20WA%2098122%2C%20United%20States&source=p2&currentTab=experience_tab&searchId=c0457467-3cdf-4f5b-ad2e-d78c4605c049&recommended_instance_id=333317Life motto: Breathe in. Breathe out.Newest life lesson: "He who rushes ahead doesn't go far." ~ Lao TzuLatest favorite bumper sticker: If it's not going right, go left.

name: Restful Room in W. Ballard-NO cleaning fee!
summary: A quiet and peaceful room with private bath in the Sunset Hill area of West Ballard in a neighborhood setting.  Plenty of street parking.  Use of the kitchen.  No cleaning fee.   Five blocks to Puget Sound and the Ballard Locks.  Excellent reviews.
space: Sunset Hills is in an area of northwest Seattle known as Ballard.  Ballard was called "Snoose Junction" until about 20 years ago when it started becoming hip.  It still has its Scandinavian roots, funkiness, and continues as a working fishing port (where the Deadliest Catch boats leave from).   "Downtown Ballard" is 8 blocks to the east where you will find great restaurants like Bastille and Walrus and the Carpenter,  incredible bakeries like Cafe Besalu, shopping, coffee shops (it is Seattle, after all), and sightseeing.   The Hiram Chittenden Locks, a popular (free) attraction and Shilshole Bay in Puget Sound are both within six blocks.  Golden Gardens, a huge, in-city park, is less than two miles and features a sandy beach, great walks and even swimming in the salt water of Puget Sound.   About a mile away walk is Discovery Park, formerly an US Army base called Fort Lawton, and now a 534 acre nature preserve owned by the Seattle Park Department.  There are lots of trails, interestin

name: 4BR Historic Home at Seattle Center
summary: Located in Seattle's Queen Anne neighborhood just a few blocks from the iconic Space Needle, this 1891 Victorian is one of the great homes of Seattle. Your stay will be memorable, not only for the exciting city just outside your door but also for the warm and historic home that is yours. Accommodations include the first and second floors together with an Airstream in the rear of the property. The grand main entrance is your private entry.
space: The main floor, a part of which is designated a Seattle landmark, includes a wonderful foyer, the living and dining areas, powder room, and kitchen. A grand staircase leads to the upper floor containing a master suite with sitting room and en suite bathroom, and two other bedrooms sharing a large bathroom with Jacuzzi tub.  The master suite has a king bed as well as a sofa bed in the sitting area.  The 2nd bedroom has a queen bed, and the 3rd has a day bed with pull out making either 2 single beds or a king-size bed.  For parties of more than 3 guests, a wonderful, new 25' Airstream in the backyard provides a fun fourth bedroom with a queen bed.  Sorry, no children are allowed in the Airstream. The house was built in 1891 and is a Seattle Landmark.  The yard has been set aside as an Urban Open Area, and a private back patio provides a great place to kick back and relax after a long day (or night). A short walk away are: Seattle Center, Space Needle, Opera House, theaters, many restaura

For parties of more than 3 guests
neighborhood_overview: The house is four blocks above the Uptown neighborhood with its many fun and fine restaurants. Uptown is adjacent to the Seattle Center where you'll find the Space Needle, Opera House, Ballet, Chilhuly Glass Museum, Experience Music Project, and much more. The following restaurants are favorites in walking distance: Toulouse Petit (Louisiana Cajun 3 blocks away), Pesos (Mexican 3 blocks away), Ten Mercer (Elegant 3 blocks away), The Mecca ("Drunks Serving Drunks since 1929" diner 3 blocks away), The Masonry (Wood-fired pizza and rotating tap beers, 3 blocks away), The Sitting Room (Paninis and wine, 2 blocks away), Pagliacci Pizza (3 blocks away), Tum Tim Thai (2 blocks away). There are great coffee shops, a Piano bar, grocery stores, and more all within that same radius.  At the top of Queen Anne Hill, there are many other restaurants as well, and great shopping.
notes: Main level (first floor) quiet hours starting at 10pm. Please, no parties or loud gatherings on the main level after that time.  Please use the parlor (living room) only for quiet reading and conversation after 9pm. To help preserve the original floors, please no shoes indoors. Please pack some slippers or warm socks. Outdoor parties should be aware of the city's restrictions: no loud music outdoors after 10pm during the week, and after 11pm on Saturday.
transit: The #1 bus picks up 2 blocks away and drops off 1 block away, for easy access to downtown.  Walking along the waterfront from the house puts you at the Olympic Sculpture Park in about 20 minutes.  Uphill a couple blocks is the famous Kinnear Park overlook of the city, as well as the wonderful walk to the Olympic Mountains vista. If you walk to Seattle Center (about 10 minutes), you can also hop on the monorail for the quick ride downtown.
access: While you'll have the main and second floors to yourself, the owners reside in the lower level reached through a separate entrance.
interaction: Mark and Nadine divide their time between Seattle and the Olympic Peninsula, and can provide great tips for vacationing all over the Northwest.

name: Private Bed & Bath in Ballard
summary: Your private bedroom has a full-sized bed for 1 or 2 people with an attached bathroom in my Ballard townhouse on the garden floor. A sliding door opens up to the shared front patio. I live upstairs on the 2nd and 3rd floors with my 2 dogs. The house is close to the downtown bus, terrific restaurants, a French bakery, indoor pool, fun shops, music venues, and a movie theater. The room is equipped with everything you need for a short or extended stay.

neighborhood_overview: Ballard is north of downtown and is popular for restaurants, bars, music venues, a movie theater, shops, the Ballard Locks & Salmon Ladder, and Shilshole Beach. Within walking distance are coffee shops and terrific restaurants. The indoor Ballard Pool is less than a block away. It's about 20-25 mins walk to Market Street and Old Ballard.
notes: I have two wonderful, people-loving dogs who may bark from upstairs when you come in the front door.
transit: Parking is free on the street. Uber, Lyft, taxi, and buses are good options to get around. The bus to the waterfront, Pike Place Market and downtown is 2 blocks away.
access: The guest room is on the ground floor of my 3-floor townhouse. It is fairly private, set off from the rest of the house, with a sliding door to the front yard that we share. Upstairs is not part of the rental and is my space with my dogs. My dogs and I spend time in the front yard sometimes, so we may see each other. You'll be using the shared front door with a coded lock.
interaction: I enjoy having guests and am available to give directions, recommendations, or to have a chat. I'm available by text and phone at any time.
house_rules: Upstairs is off limits to guests at this time. Thank you!
host_about: I've lived in Seattle for 26 years. I love it here, even when it rains. I love being outdoors with my dogs, at the dog park, on a hike, or just walking around the neighborhood. I am a certified life coach, write stories and poetry, and love taking photographs. This is my second year as an Airbnb host and I've enjoyed meeting so many people, from so many different places! Every single guest is interesting.

The space is within easy walking distance to the delights of Ballard and is located in a charming neighborhood. There is no interior shared common space and no access to cooking facilities. space: The suite is attached to the garage with easy access to the alley.  It is a large (10x13) room with private bathroom. It includes a queen size bed, small table / desk and a walk in shower. You are most welcome to visit with our chickens, grab raspberries or strawberries if they are ripe during your visit. summary: Queen Anne Hill is a charming neighborhood with historic old homes, located just up the hill from The Seattle Center (Space Needle, etc.) Close enough to be convenient to everything, yet just far enough away from the traffic, hubbub and commotion of downtown!

Queen Anne Hill is a charming neighborhood with historic old homes, located just up the hill from The Seattle Center (Space Needle, etc.) Close enough to be convenient to everything, yet just far enough away from the traffic, hubbub and commotion of downtown! neighborhood_overview: Queen Anne Hill is a wonderful and historic area of Seattle with amazing views! From the street that rings the top of the hill one can view Mt. Rainier, the Space Needle and downtown Seattle, Elliot Bay, the Olympic Mountains, Lake Union, and the Cascade Mountains! Bring your camera!
notes: We will provide you with a Parking Pass to hang from your rear view mirror. Free street parking in front of our house.
transit: The bus stop is just two and a half blocks from our house and goes directly downtown.
access: The private apartment has its own private entrance.
interaction: We like to greet our guests and show them around the apartment. Following that, we are always available to answer questions about Queen Anne Hill, Seattle sights and provide recommendations should you knock on our door.
house_rules: Check-in: 3:00 p.m. Check-out: 10:00 a.m. No smokers or pets. Please leave shoes on the boot mat! It helps keep the outside outside. (Bring slippers.) Please leave the kitchen as you found it. We will email you additional info including entry code a week before your visit. (If you don't receive this email, please check your spam folder!) And the most important rule: relax and have fun during your visit to Seattle! Thanks. See you soon!
host_about: Eileen and Ray were born in Seattle just three blocks from each other, finally met at the University of Washington, and have lived on Queen Anne Hill since college. They've been in love for over forty-six years, are young-at-heart and enjoy hiking and skiing. (They rack up more than 85 days of skiing every season!) Eileen loves to read, take walks around Queen Anne Hill, and "putter" in her garden and Ray hikes up Tiger Mountain east of Seattle to go paragliding as often as weather permits! They are delighted to welcome you to the basement apartment in their 1904 home where they've lived for over forty years. Ray worked as a graphic artist, magazine publisher, advertising director and restaurant general manager. Nowadays when he's not flying or skiing, he works with wood and steel in his workshop. Eileen worked in the accounting department of a local TV station and loves her daily walks around Seattle, skiing and relaxing with a good book and cup of tea. Ray and Eileen love the opportunity that hosting with Airbnb for over five years has afforded them: the chance to meet wonderful people from all over the world!Eileen & Ray look forward to meeting you and welcoming you to Seattle!

neighborhood_overview: Located just 4 miles from downtown Seattle - on the bus line.  The neighborhood is a wonderful central location for seeing the sights of Seattle. One mile from the University of Washington (UW); 1 mile from Green Lake (the running and dog watching mecca of Seattle); 2 blocks from the Wednesday afternoon farmer's market; I mile from Woodland Park Zoo; 2 miles from Fremont and the Sunday market.  1 mile from the Burke-Gilman trail for biking. neighborhood_overview: West Seattle, while a part of the City of Seattle, has it's own small town feel.  Neighborly, friendly and helpful people. Of course there are many coffee shops.  There's an old, historic movie theater that has been remodeled into a fourplex and is now showing first run films.  The upstairs area has a beer/wine bar!  Sip while you watch! We also have a nice, new live theater with several stages for all sorts of performances.  There is often a Broadway type show on the main stage, and maybe jazz in a smaller area.  The theater has an art gallery on the main floor. There are numerous restaurants of all types, many in the less expensive range.  Something for everyone. There is one huge waterfront park (Lincoln Park) and many smaller parks scattered around the neighborhood.  This is a great walking and biking area.  Along the beach area on the north end of West Seattle you can rent all sorts of bikes and boats; check out Wheel Fun Rentals. in, so I hope you will be happy here too.
notes: The house is on a narrow, curvy lane.  Traffic goes both ways so it is important to drive carefully and be prepared to pull off to the side if needed to allow another car to proceed.  Speed limit is 15 mph!
transit: The public transportation is a bus system.  There is one bus line that is very close, but limited in its schedule.  There are other bus lines, but you would need to walk a minimum of 3/4 miles to get to a bus stop. They can take you downtown, or other locations to change buses. Most of my guests do choose to rent a car.  There is parking for one average size car.  Lyft has become a good alternative and might compete with the cost of a rental car for city trips. The West Seattle water taxi takes 10 to 15 minutes to downtown Seattle.  You can check it out online. (website hidden)
access: Guests have access to the patio area in front of their front door, and a deck off the patio with tables and chairs. There is an outdoor fireplace for very careful people!  (Sometimes there are burn bans, especially in summer fire hazard months.)  You can also use beach chairs, cooler, and beach umbrellas if you'd like.
interaction: I assume most people would like privacy for their visit, and we don't interfere with that.  I'm available for help if needed, and always like to hear if there is something that would improve your stay.
house_rules: No smoking of any kind indoors, please.  No incense burning.  Pets only under certain circumstances, and approved before renting.  Rental for named guests only.  PLEASE do not invite others.  No parties.  (This is a quiet location.)   There is parking for one average size car or small SUV.  If you have another size vehicle, please let me know BEFORE booking and I will explain where you can park.
host_about: I've stayed at AirBnb lodgings and it worked out just great.  I have two grown kids and the best granddaughter ever. I've lived in Seattle a long time so I can help you with places to go and things to do, directions and transportation, if you want.  I look forward to meeting you.

notes: If you are using public transport, it is easy to catch the bus within a block, either the #7 or #9.  Just north about two miles is the Mt Baker train. There is a crossfit gym available within one block and many others within minutes over Rainier Valley.

neighborhood_overview: Home is located on a quiet, tree-lined street in a moderately upscale neighborhood-close to all that Seattle and West Seattle have to offer. Your room and hallway are decorated tastefully with Picasso and Matisse. You have  available  in your room a clock, radio, umbrella, and a 800 lumen flashlight for any unexpected power failures.  Sunsets at Alki beach are known for their gorgeous beauty.   You can watch the brightly lit (or sunlit on a nice day) Seattle skyline from the beach. Many restaurants on Alki beach  as well as Admiral Juction to satisfy your foodie gene-e.g: Cactus, Phoenicia, Salty's Seafood Restaurant, Marination Place, Tully's, Top Pot, Pegasus Pizza, a Thai restaurant, Duke's sea food restaurant, Blue Moon burgers, all within 5 to 10 minutes by car and 15-20 minutes by foot. Circa, Swinery, Copper Coin, Metropolitan Market food court (organic and gourmet) and many more restaurants available in Admiral Junction and on Alki beach.  Want to watch one of the newer movies?
notes: This is our  ground-floor listing with a maximum guest limit of 2 sharing one queen bed. No sleeping bags allowed on the floor for extra bed space.  This is not suitable for children. Guests enjoy their own private bathroom right next to their bedroom.  Plenty of FREE parking on the street if you are driving. We respect diversity and invite people of all ethnicities, genders, sexual orientations, religions, national origin etc. We have another listing on the 3rd floor for one guest. You may run into the host or the top-floor guest in the shared kitchen/dining area.   Booking must be done by the guest. Third party bookings are permitted only with host permission. Please contact the host, if you are booking this for a relative such as  parents or in-laws.
transit: Please download the app 'Transit' or use (Hidden by Airbnb) maps to find out routes.  By plugging the address you want to be at, they give detailed direction on when and what bus to take. Bus routes 55, 56 and 57 take you back and forth directly to Seattle downtown during the rush hours in the morning and evening on week days. At other times Route 50 and Rapid Ride (C) take you to Seattle. Bus stop for 50, 56 and 57 is within a 4-minute walk. 50 and Rapid Ride C run almost until midnight. Catch 55 and 128 (goes to Alaska juncion) at California Avenue stop across from Safeway by Circa restaurant. Take 128 to Alaska junction to take C line to Seattle down town which takes 15-20 minutes to downtown. My experience with Uber and Lyft - they are always hovering nearby and usually come within a few minutes.  There is a FREE shuttle #775 provided by public transportation from this area to take you to the beach and also to water taxi until 7:00 pm  if you want to try it for the fun of it or to
access: Please provide accurate check-in time  within one-hour range. (e.g 4:00-5:00 pm or 5:00 to 6:00 pm etc). Feel free to use the kitchen and dining area for your food and drink consumption. There is smart TV in your room to view Netflix shows. Living room TV is for host use only.
interaction: Interaction with guests  is as needed to help you get the best use of your space and amenities. Your comfort is the priority. I am always available to answer questions within the hour using Air BNB text platform. Privacy-both mine and yours- is valued and every effort is made to ensure such.
house_rules: No smoking or pets allowed in or near the home. This is not a Marijuana  or Tobacco friendly home and  such use is not permitted. No unregistered guests in the home please. Please enjoy your food and beverages in the kitchen/dining area only.  Please leave your shoes on the shoe tray in the hallway between the bedroom and bathroom on the ground floor for the purpose of hygiene.  I would make every effort to orient you in person depending on your arrival time. If you are booking for you and another person we need information about them such as their name, occupation, your relationship with them etc.  If they are registered Air BNB users they are already verified. If they are not, we may ask to see their ID.  Third Party bookings are not allowed for this listing.  You must book for yourself and your guest together if you are booking for two people.

host_about: Nathan and I are an easy going couple who loves traveling and seeing new places. We love taking our family to the beach whether it's the Washington coast, Hawaii, or Portugal!Nathan is an IT professional who runs our home brewery in his spare time. I am a registered nurse working at a local non-profit. We are parents of two little boys, a fluffy cat, and a friendly pup who loves everyone. We are friendly, down to earth people who strive to treat everyone with kindness and respect. We love our city and are eager to share with our guests all our favorite spots (check out my guidebook!) We value Seattle for it's friendly people, diverse and delicious foods, its amazing natural beauty and fun outdoor activities. As hosts we like to greet people in person when they arrive and make sure the check in process goes smoothly. We strive to give our guests space and privacy while also making ourselves available to answer questions and provide recommendations about the local area as needed.

name: Cozy Seattle Apartment Near UW & Children's
summary: Close to: UW Campus, Children‰Ûªs & UW Hospitals, U Village, Burke-Gilman Trail, Magnuson Park, & Lake Washington; easy 7 minute drive to: I-5 & just 1 exit to Capitol Hill, 2 to Queen Anne & 3 to Downtown; easy walk to: PCC & Metropolitan Markets, & multiple bus routes to: UW Light Rail Station, Downtown, & all of Seattle.
space: Cosy & clean one bedroom/one bathroom lower level apartment in home.  At 700 square feet, the apartment is spacious with a full kitchen, washer/dryer, gas fireplace, & a tankless/on-demand water heater (so that hot water does not run out mid-shower).  Located in a quiet, beautiful, & safe residential neighborhood that is ideally situated for walking & biking, with dining, shopping & groceries nearby.  Large sunny yard has organic fruit & vegetable gardens, mature trees, & a picnic table. The apartment is very comfortably furnished with a king size Duxiana bed (this is an especially comfortable bed), two full size couches, a large desk, dining table, & reading library. WiFi & Wii. The apartment is ideal for both long & short term stays. Due to our close proximity to the UW, we have enjoyed hosting visiting professors, students, & scholars for extended stays; as well as medical residents for Children's & UW hospitals.

neighborhood_overview: The apartment is located in one of Seattle's wonderful walkable, bike-able, & bus-able neighborhoods. Situated in a quiet, safe, & beautiful residential neighborhood, a short walk will bring guests to two excellent markets, bus routes to Downtown & all areas of Seattle, & the Burke-Gilman walking & riding trail. Abundant shopping & restaurant options are a short & easy drive to U Village & other local neighborhood businesses including Ventoux coffee roaster & cafe, Queen Mary Tea Room, Frank's Oyster House & Champagne Parlor, & Mioposto wood fired pizzeria--all 2 minutes by car or around 10 by foot. Situated at the foot of View Ridge, a 5-10 minute uphill walk leads to the top of the ridge where there are beautiful sunset views in the evening, as well as views of Mt. Rainer, Lake Washington, the Cascades, & Mt. Baker on clear days as you walk through lovely residential neighborhoods. Activities include swimming & hiking at 350 acre Magnuson Park with its mile long stretch of Lake Washi
notes: For guests with allergies or chemical sensitivities, the apartment is cleaned, & the laundry is washed, with natural cleaning solutions that are free & clear of fragrances & dyes. I also provide natural soap & shampoo that are scented with natural oils.
transit: I-5 is 7 minutes away, with exits to Capitol Hill, Queen Anne, & Downtown 1, 2, & 3 exits away. There are bus stops at either end of our street with routes to Downtown, UW Light Rail Station, & all areas of Seattle. The bus ride to the UW Light Rail Station is about 20 minutes. The light rail runs about every 6 minutes with a 6 minute ride to Capitol Hill & another few minutes to downtown. If you like to bike ride, the Burke-Gilman wends through the University, Fremont, & Ballard neighborhoods. If you prefer walking, it is a beautiful sheltered trail through mostly wooded & residential areas.
access: Guests have a separate entrance & parking space.
interaction: Guests have their own private apartment. I welcome guests at check-in & show them around the apartment, explaining where to find things & how they work. If guests would like, I also make visit suggestions based on their interests. I am available by text & email throughout their stay to answer any questions. After the check-in welcome, I base interactions on guest preference: some guests enjoy more interaction, while others are more independent. My goal as a host is for guests to feel welcome & that they have a comfortable home-away-from-home during their stay in Seattle.
house_rules: The apartment has one king size bed & is ideal for 1 or 2  clean & quiet guests. I'm glad to host guests who are new to Airbnb & therefore do not have host recommendations, but require a reservation request to determine whether they would be a good fit for the apartment--so please get in touch if you are new to Airbnb!
host_about: I enjoy writing, making art, gardening & cooking.  I am able to walk or ride my bike for most local outings because our home is right next to the Burke-Gilman bike trail.

neighborhood_overview: This is a fun & interesting international neighborhood with lots of quirky shops and tons of food choices - including a great sushi restaurant right in our building. There's quick take-out to high end, and everything in between. Uwajimaya Asian specialty supermarket is close by, plus coffee shops & bakeries - you won't go hungry in this neighborhood! ‰Û¢ Check our online Guidebook to see all the great restaurants & attractions we've bookmarked in our neighborhood. We also have a guidebook in the room when you arrive with some of our favorite spots nearby for food, plus maps and other details. ‰Û¢ We're just a few blocks from the baseball & soccer/football stadiums. There are many bars and clubs within walking distance, and even more just a quick bus ride away. Since the building is right downtown you can also easily visit the Seattle Art Museum, Sculpture Park, Pike Place Market, the Space Needle, Experience Music Project, and many other great Seattle attractions. ‰Û¢ Please note that we're
notes: There is a long flight of stairs to get up to our floor and no elevator. Also you need to climb a ladder to get up into the bed loft. And finally just want to make triple sure you've noticed this has a shared bathroom. (Remember to mention the secret code word TEDDY to let us know our place is perfect for you!)
transit: ‰Û¢ We're perfectly located for all forms of public transportation: the Light Rail train stop is one block away for easy, affordable access to SeaTac airport; the AmTrak train station is also just a few blocks away; quick easy access to many bus routes, including the Bolt Bus; the waterfront with ferry terminals is just a short walk away. ‰Û¢ Street parking is free after 8pm till 7am, and there are many pay-to-park lots all around us.  ‰Û¢ If you'll be using a lot of public transportation you might want to buy an Orca Card ($5). You can load it up with however much $ you'd like, and then use it for quicker access when boarding the Light Rail train, buses, etc. Orca kiosks can be found near the ticket & boarding areas at most transportation hubs.  ‰Û¢ When you check out, feel free to leave your Orca card on the desk for future guests to use.
interaction: Our style is to give guests total privacy, but to be available if you need anything. Some guests arrive in the evening and might feel uncomfortable asking questions late at night - so we've tried to provide as much info as possible to help you figure things out. You'll see some post-it notes in the shared spaces, which most people find helpful, (but some find irritating - sorry!) There's also a guidebook on the desk in the room which will hopefully answer most of your questions. But please don't be shy if you need something or have questions. We're easy to reach, and often we're close by during the day working somewhere in the building.
house_rules: Please be sure to read our house rules & our entire description about THE SPACE before booking - and look for our *secret code word*! ‰Û¢ 2 guests max - 1 or 2 guests sharing the bed. The small couch is not meant as an extra bed, and unfortunately we cannot accommodate extra guests.   ‰Û¢ 2 week max ‰Û¢ check-in time during winter months is more flexible - let us know what is ideal for you (you can also drop off luggage early)    ‰Û¢ check-out is usually by noon - but right now during winter months you can ask about a later check-out (you can also store luggage after)     ‰Û¢ no smoking or vaping of any kind inside the building ‰Û¢ bathrooms & kitchenette are shared ‰Û¢ you'll need to climb a ladder to get up into the bed ‰Û¢ we supply all bedding & towels, and have a very comfortable bed - read our many reviews! The shared bathroom with the shower has shampoo, body wash, conditioner, body lotion, Q-tips & other misc. There's also a hair dryer under the sink, and an iron & ironing board in the other b
host_about: Hi, we're a married couple living and working in downtown Seattle. We started hosting on airbnb about 6 years ago and we love it! We travel and use airbnb just like you, so we understand what it's like to be a guest. As you can see from our many reviews, we'll do our best to make your stay easy & comfortable. If you have any questions just get in touch!

name: 2BR/1BA Quiet Capitol Hill Bungalow w/Loft
summary: WalkScore 97! A quiet and cozy retreat in the center of it all. This sleepy little 6 unit garden court complex was built in 1923 and updated in 2006. Just steps away you'll find shops, restaurants and groceries; a little farther  Volunteer Park & Cal Anderson Park or bustling nightlife. Our bungalow is located in Seattle's charming North Capitol Hill neighborhood within a short walk of most of Seattle's sights, and just blocks from the new Link Light Rail and Capitol Hill Streetcar stops.
space: Whether you're coming for business or pleasure, for a weekend, week or to spend the summer the Bungalow off Broadway is the perfect place to get away to. This cozy 2BR/1BA getaway home has its own front and back doors behind a secured gate with a central garden courtyard shared by the 6 units, which were built in 1923 and remodeled in 2006. The living area is furnished with comfortable and stylish sofas from Dania, and Brazilian cherry flooring. This is a great place to relax, catch up on the day's news and enjoy a glass of wine. The kitchen features stainless steel throughout, marble countertops, ample daylight with windows looking out onto the garden courtyard. You'll find a queen-size pillow-top bed in the bedroom, and another queen-size bed in the loft. The bonus loft is also a great place to retreat to with a book.  Note: The loft is only accessible via the built-in ladder, and is not suitable for children under 5 or for people not physically able to safely climb a ladder. The loc

neighborhood_overview: Most of the Hill's major thoroughfares are dotted with coffeehouses, taverns and bars, and residences cover the gamut from modest motel-like studio apartment buildings to some of the city's grandest and most venerable mansions. The neighborhood figures prominently in nightlife and entertainment, with many bars hosting live music and with numerous fringe theatres. At night enthusiastic (and at times eccentric) people fill the streets in the Pike/Pine corridor (about a half mile away) enjoying the diverse entertainment and the culture of openness and acceptance. Spontaneous street parties have been known to break out with music playing and people dancing in the streets like on Election Day 2008 and the freak snow storm in December 2008 (snow is very unusual in Seattle and can stifle transit). In these instances, police officers observe but will usually let the revelling continue. When clubs do shut down at around 2 AM, people can now flock to the plethora of new street vendors opening up
notes: I try to keep the Guidebook attached to the listing current, relevant and helpful for our guests. Please use it! And if you find something you that needs correcting or that you thing should be included please let me know, we want all our guests to get the most out of their time in our little bungalow!
transit: I recommend walking. When I lived at the bungalow I didn't have a car and never missed it. You can walk to downtown, the Pike Place Market, the Convention Center, Volunteer Park and Cal Anderson Park, hundreds of shops and restaurants, theaters, bars, taverns and transit stations.  The new Sound Transit Link Light Rail station has opened just blocks from the bungalow, and can get you to the University District/Husky Stadium, downtown, SODO, Rainier Valley and the airport. There's also a new Capitol Hill Streetcar which runs down broadway and can take you around Capitol Hill and to the International District. Pro tip: leave the car at home, you won't need it and you won't miss it!
access: You'll have access to our entire home and all of it's amenities, including the coin-free washer and dryer downstairs. You're free to enjoy the communal seating areas in the garden courtyard as well.
interaction: I work full-time and will respond to questions as soon as I'm able. Sometimes this might mean waiting until lunch or after work, but I do try to respond as soon as I possibly can.  We do check things out regularly and replace appliances and amenities as needed, so we don't anticipate any problems, but just in case I also have a handyman available nearby to help in the unlikely event you do encounter any problems.
house_rules: Thank you in advance for respecting our house rules, they are very important to us. Quiet hours at The Bungalows are from 10PM until 8AM, so please keep noise to a reasonable volume so as to not disturb our neighbors, and don't host parties or get-togethers in our little bungalow - it's really just not set up for such events.  Seattle invented curbside recycling and the city takes recycling very seriously and issues fines for failure to recycle. Garbage and recycling bins are provided in the unit for your convenience - please help us comply with the law and keep recyclables separated from your trash.  Please take care with the keys and guest parking pass during your stay and be sure to replace them when you check out. The guest parking pass in particular is expensive and difficult to replace. There is a $50 fee for lost keys and a $150 replacement fee for failure to return the parking pass. When it's time to check-out please leave our home in the same condition you found it when you ar
host_about: I grew up in Seattle, and while I've lived as far away as Buenos Aires I've always considered Seattle home. I love the diverse neighborhoods Seattle has to offer, the great craftsman architecture, and the beautiful gardens you can find all over the city. Seattle is a photographer's dream.

host_about: I'am Hispanic woman from Peru.  I have been living in the USA for last 37 years. I worked as Registered Nurse for 30 years and loves to be a great hostess for my  family and friends.   I love cooking, swimming, walking, exercising, dancing and karaoke, and traveling.My house is well known by the counsel of Peru in Seattle W.A., honorable Mr. Miguel Angel Velasquez as "THE 5-STAR HOUSE" "LA CASA DE LAS 5 ESTRELLAS", because only  VIP people from Peru had come for different occasions and receptions or just to visit Seattle:  From Politicians, congressman, commanders from the Peruvian military, Doctors, Engineers, Mayors of different cities, Directors of Hospital and Universities,  top musicians from Peru and even the presidents of Peru, I had also been invited to Presidential Inaugurations which has been such great experience be able to not only see them but be close to all presidents of the US as well from Peru.  My house has gain a great respect among all my friends, family and friends from around my community. I hope you like art and paints because I have some beautiful murals in my house and colorful. Even the family room has sky with 1/4 of a moon, the sunset, and the stars at night that you can feel outdoors all the time day and night. It is exited, as  well as quiet, friendly and spotless for you. I will be waiting for you at any time or day. If you are interesting in trying some Peruvian food I can cook it for you, prepare sack lunches to take to your seminars, classes or tours, I can be your guide, driver, laundry needs, dry cleaner services and what ever you need count with my help.As a Registered Nurse I specialized being a good therapist listening and advising people with their problems, specially those that has been experiencing a bad divorces, death in the family.  I am here to hear you and listen to you at free of charge.  Also if you need to practice your Spanish I can do this at free of charge.Thank you,Flor Cruz

name: Relaxing Garden Cottage w/ Hot Tub!
summary: Relax and enjoy the privacy of your own Seattle garden cottage with hot tub, dedicated guest parking spot, and easy access to Downtown Seattle via public transit. Columbia City is hip and happening, and close to the lake with some of the best parks in the city. Your host Julie is welcoming and full of all of the Seattle expertise and tips you will need to have a fantastic getaway.
space: Welcome! Relax and enjoy the privacy of your own Seattle garden cottage with easy access to Downtown Seattle. Your getaway cottage is centrally located just 18 minutes from SeaTac airport and downtown Seattle. The clean and easy Light Rail is exactly a half mile from the cottage as are many express buses within a couple of blocks. Walk 5 minutes to vibrant and historic Columbia City with loads of great restaurants, a fantastic natural foods grocery, cafe and deli called the PCC, art galleries, cinema, live music and theater, 3 yoga studios and a historic library. Search for Columbia City in NY Times for a helpful travel review. Your accommodations include a bright cozy cottage, supremely comfortable Queen sized bed, sky lights, 3/4 bathroom, ceiling fan, gas fireplace, wet bar kitchen, complimentary snacks, soda water, tea and coffee, WIFI, and French doors opening onto your private outdoor covered patio overlooking a zen garden.
